      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Nothing is known of George Shove other than the information given in the collection.  He was evidently a  
	  general merchant, selling everything from molasses to nails.  The location of his store cannot be 
	  definitively determined, but if he is of the same family as the creators of the <archref href="../s/shove_bowen.htm">Shove, Bowen and Shove Account Book</archref> (see Related Material below), it may have been 
	  in Freetown, Massachusetts or thereabouts.</p>
	  
	  </bioghist>
	        
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">George Shove Account Book</emph> consists of one volume, a ledger containing 
		 credits and debits for various patrons of the merchant 
		 George Shove.  Items sold include molasses, rum, sugar, shoes, corn, flaxseed and cloth.  
		 Items listed in the credit column include wood, coal, "days worked," curing and tanning services, and hoops (whether 
		 dress or barrel is not specified).  Occasionally food items are listed, such as herring and  "a pig."</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
